===Verb===
{{en-verb|slays|slaying|slew|past2=slayed|slain|past_ptc2=slayed}}

# {{lb|en|now|_|literary}} To [[kill]], [[murder]].
#: ''The knight '''slew''' the dragon.''
#: ''Our foes must all be '''slain'''.''
# {{lb|en|literary}} To [[eradicate]] or [[stamp out]].
#: ''You must '''slay''' these thoughts.''
# {{lb|en|by extension|colloquial}} To [[defeat]], [[overcome]] (in a competition or contest).
#* '''1956''', “Giants '''Slay''' Bears in Pro Title Battle”, in ''Lodi News-Sentinel'', 1956 December 31, [http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WSMzAAAAIBAJ&pg=5705,7365754&dq=slay page 8].
#* '''1985''', “Redskins '''slay''' Giants; Thiesmann shatters leg”, in ''The Gadsden Times'', 1985 November 19, [http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2cIfAAAAIBAJ&pg=2781,3776224&dq=slay page D1-5].
#* '''1993''', Jack Curry, “[http://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/21/sports/baseball-yanks-bullpen-falls-short-again.html Yanks’ Bullpen Falls Short Again]”, in ''The New York Times'', 1993 April 21:
#*: The Yankees were actually '''slayed''' by two former Yankees because Rich Gossage pitched one scoreless inning in relief of Eckersley to notch his first victory.
# {{lb|en|slang}} To [[delight]] or [[overwhelm]], especially with [[laughter]].
#: ''Ha ha! You '''slay''' me!''
# {{lb|en|slang|ambitransitive}}<!--including LGBT and AAVE--> To [[amaze]], [[stun]] or otherwise incapacitate by [[awesomeness]]; to be [[awesome]] at something; to [[kill]] {{qual|slang sense}}.

=====Usage notes=====
* The alternative past tense and past participle form "[[slayed]]" is most strongly associated with the slang sense, "to delight or overwhelm":
*: {{quote-book|i2=*::|1929|Harry Charles Witwer|Yes Man's Land|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3K1EAAAAIAAJ|page=254
|passage="Cutey, you '''slayed''' me !" grins Jackie, working fast. "I guess that's what made the rest of 'em look so bad — you was so good!"}}
* In recent use, "slayed" is also often found associated with the other senses as well. However, this is widely considered nonstandard.<ref>"But ''slayed'' cannot be considered established in such use. Whether it eventually becomes established remains to be seen." — {{cite-book|title=Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2yJusP0vrdgC&pg=PA853&dq=%2Bslayed|isbn=0877791325|author=Merriam-Webster Publishing Co.|page=853|chapter=slay|year=1994}}</ref>
* A review of US usage 2000-2009 in COCA suggests that "slayed" is increasing in popularity, but remains less common than "slew". It is very rare in UK usage (BNC).
* "Slain" has a current usage in newspaper headlines, as being shorter than "murdered".

